titleStmt.title: Istanbul, Topkapı Palace Museum (Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi), "Saray 50386" (Gotthelf Bergsträßer archives) [= Karatay 42]

msIdentifier.repository: Topkapı Palace Museum (Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi) , Istanbul

summary.p: 605 fol., Parchment; Shelfmark: "Saray 50386" (Gotthelf Bergsträßer archives); Qurʾānic Text: Q 2:12- Q 114; Lines per page: 14; Dimensions: 290 x 365 mm (according to Karatay, 1962); Script style: kūfī, type F.I (described in François Déroche's Abbasid Tradition, pp.46-47), see Palaeography by Salome Beridze; Estimated date of production: 750-900; Unknown provenance.

This entry is based on black-and-white photos of a manuscript labelled as "Sarayı 50386" in the archives of Gotthelf Bergsträßer. Photos were taken around 1930 presumably in the collection of Topkapı Sarayı. One image is reproduced in Gotthelf Bergsträßer's Geschichte des Qoran as "Tafel VI" with the caption: "Abbildung 7. Istanbul, Saray 50386 Format 30 x 40 cm Sure 93, 4-94,3" (which corresponds to fol. 596v). All folio number in this digital entry are based on the numbering given in the photos counting 605 folios. The manuscript seems to correspond to shelfmark Y. 4562 of the catalogue of Topkapı Sarayı written by Fehmi Ethem Karatay, 1962, p. 16: "42 Y. 4562 Aynı Parşömen. 290mm boy ve 365mm eninde cönk şeklinde 606 yaprak. Sahifede kûfî yazı ile 300mm uzunl.[uğunda] 14 satır. Tahminen III. (IX) asırda yazılmıştır. Baştan 3 yaprağı ile sure başları tezhiplidir. III. Osman’ın vakıf mührünü ve kaydını havidir. Tahta üzerine kahve rengi deri cildin kapakları arabesk geçmelerle süslü olup üst kapağın tezyınatı mustal[t]il ve alt kapağının müdevver şekildedir; üzerinde demir halkalar vardır. Bu mushafın baş kısmı eksik olup Baḳara (2) suresinin 13. ayeti ile başlar."Fethi Edhem Karatay, Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi Arapça Yazmalar Kataloğu: Kur’an, Kur’an İlimleri, Tefsirler (İstanbul: Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi Yayınları, 1962), vol. 1, p. 16. Karatay's catalogue entry was translated by Esra Gözeler and Tuba Karaşahin as follows: "42 Y. 4562 Same Parchment. 606 junk shaped leaves of 290 mm height and 365 mm width. The text area written in Kufic script [contains] 14 lines measuring 300 mm. Probably copied during the 3rd (9th) century. Its first three leaves and sūra beginnings are gilded. Contains waqf registration and seal of Osman III. The covers of the brown leather binding on wooden [board] are decorated with interlaced arabesque [forms]. The decoration of the upper cover is rectangular, and the lower cover is circular and there are iron rings on it. The beginning of this codex is missing, and it starts with Q 2:13 (Sūra al-Baqara)." Karatay lists 606 fol., one folio more than we have images from Bergsträßer. Since the codex starts with Q 2:12 the original codex is supposed to have had one folio more than the codex preserved in the Topkapi collection, 606 folios.

The Khalili Collections (London) preserve three folios of a Qurʾān written in the same script style (KFQ 46, KFQ 47, KFQ 71). In his catalogue entry about these fragments F. Déroche refers to the image given in Bergsträßer's Geschichte des Qoran and connects it to the catalogue in Karatay, 1962 "no. 42" (However the call number he mentions, Y. 744" does not correspond to Karatay no. 42 which list this manuscript as "Y. 4562"). In order to verify Karatay's entry, its echo in Déroche's Abbasid Tradition ( KFQ 46, KFQ 47, KFQ 71) and the black-and-white images given in this entry, direct consultation of the manuscript is required. Regardless of the question about the call number, Bergsträßer's images attest an almost complete codex of the Qurʾān in this particular script style (kūfī F.I), datable to the 8th or 9th century.

The script style is kūfī type F.I. The lower return of ʾalif in the independent form is sometimes flatter and longer than in other cases. The letter group ǧīm/ḥāʾ/ḫāʾ shows the same form in the final and isolated position: the tail of the letter has no final loop and lies flat on the base line. This is different in some other F.I manuscripts, where the letter in the final form has a tail that turns back on itself. As for the letter ʿain or ġain, the final form has a circular ending that is open to the right, whereas in the isolated position the letter has a long horizontal tail, as the ǧīm/ḥāʾ/ḫāʾ group. In all other respects, the script is identical to F.I. described in François Déroche's Abbasid Tradition, pp.46-47. (Salome Beridze)
